Consider the following program with loop invariants annotated with the respective loop(s):
```
#define assume(e) if(!(e)) return 0;
extern int unknown(void);
extern int unknown_int(void);

int nondet(){
  int x;
  return x;
}

int main ()
{
  int x = 0;
  int y = 0;
  int z;

  /*@
loop invariant x >= 0;
loop invariant y >= 0;
loop invariant x == 10*y;
loop invariant x == 10 * y;
loop invariant \unchanged(z);
loop invariant 0 <= x;
loop invariant 0 <= y;
*/
while (unknown_int()){
    x += 10;
    y += 1;
  }

  if (x <= z && y >= z + 1)
    goto ERROR;

    return 0;

  ERROR:{; //@ assert(\false);
};
}
```

The verifier returns the following message.
```
Annotation error on line 21: unbound logic function \unchanged. Ignoring loop annotation
```
If an invariant is marked as Unknown, it means that the verifier could not prove it to be inductive.
If an invariant is marked as Partially Proven, it means that the verifier was depending on another assertion/loop invariant to prove its inductiveness.
If an invariant is marked as Valid, it means that the verifier was able to prove it to be inductive.
There could be errors in the loop annotation(s), other than the ones mentioned in the above error message from the verifier.
Please fix all the errors, and provide the corrected loop invariants for the program that is sufficient to verify the post-condition in the program.
Use the ACSL syntax to specify the invariants.

The program given has some invalid loop invariants and a few redundant ones. Here's a corrected version of the loop invariants:

```
#define assume(e) if(!(e)) return 0;
extern int unknown(void);
extern int unknown_int(void);

int nondet(){
  int x;
  return x;
}

int main ()
{
  int x = 0;
  int y = 0;
  int z;

  /*@
    loop invariant x >= 0;
    loop invariant y >= 0;
    loop invariant x == 10 * y;
  */
  while (unknown_int()){
    x += 10;
    y += 1;
  }

  if (x <= z && y >= z + 1)
    goto ERROR;

  return 0;

  ERROR:{; //@ assert(\false);
};
}
```

I removed the redundant loop invariants (`0 <= x` and `0 <= y` are the same as `x >= 0` and `y >= 0`). Also, I removed the invalid loop invariant `\unchanged(z)` since `\unchanged` is not supported in ACSL for loops. The remaining invariants are sufficient to verify the post-condition in the program.

